  "prompt": "How cold can the Gobi Desert get, and how do its average temperatures compare to the ones in the Great Basin Desert?",
  "response": "The Gobi Desert can experience quite cold temperatures, especially during the winter months. Temperatures in the Gobi can drop as low as -40\u00b0C (-40\u00b0F). The desert is characterized by its harsh continental climate, with significant temperature variations. Summers can be extremely hot, while winters are bitterly cold.\n\nIn comparison, the Great Basin Desert, located in the United States, also exhibits significant temperature variations, but it tends to be milder overall. Winter temperatures in the Great Basin Desert can drop to around -20\u00b0C (-4\u00b0F), which is cold but generally not as extreme as the Gobi Desert. Summers in the Great Basin are hot, with daytime temperatures frequently reaching around 30\u00b0C to 40\u00b0C (86\u00b0F to 104\u00b0F).\n\nOverall, the Gobi Desert is known for its more extreme cold temperatures in winter compared to the Great Basin Desert, although both deserts have significant seasonal temperature differences.",
